<section xml:id="intervals">
  <title>Intervals</title>
  <p>
    In addition to open and closed sets in <m>\RR^n</m>,
    the is a direct extension of intervals.
  </p>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        An <term>open interval</term> in <m>\RR^n</m> is a set of points <m>(x_1, x_2, \ldots,
        x_n) \in \RR^n</m> such that
        <me>
          a_1 \lt  x_1 \lt  b_1, \hspace{1cm} a_2 \lt  x_2 \lt  b_2, \hspace{1cm} \ldots \hspace{1cm} a_n \lt  x_n \lt  b_n
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        It is written
        <me>
          I = (a_1,b_1)\times (a_2,b_2) \times \ldots \times (a_n,b_n)
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        An <term>closed interval</term> in <m>\RR^n</m> is a set of points <m>(x_1, x_2, \ldots,
        x_n) \in \RR^n</m> such that
        <me>
          a_1 \leq x_1 \leq b_1, \hspace{1cm} a_2 \leq x_2 \leq b_2, \hspace{1cm} \ldots \hspace{1cm} a_n \leq x_n \leq b_n
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        It is written
        <me>
          I = [a_1,b_1]\times [a_2,b_2] \times \ldots \times [a_n,b_n]
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    Intervals are rectangular objects.
    In <m>\RR^2</m>, there are filled-in rectangles,
    including the hollow bounding rectangle if the interval is closed and excluding it if the interval is open.
    In <m>\RR^3</m>,
    intervals are solid rectangular prisms whose boundaries are rectangular boxes.
    In higher dimensions,
    we think of intervals are higher-dimensional rectangular prisms.
  </p>
</section>